Hard truth: hotlines aren't the answer unless they connect people with resources directly. People need food, housing, healthcare (which should include access to mental health resources), and so much more. Sometimes even "checking up" on your folks isn't enough, and that's not your fault. We have all endured much pain and suffering that we share in common. People don't want to be here, and we should name that rather than make statements that minimize the conditions we are forced to deal with daily like "joy will come again, you just have to believe it." There have been times I did not want to be here, and just because I do not think it now does not mean I can't think this way tomorrow. And all of it will return to how much I am FORCED to endure. I do not endure pain to feed the "strong Black people" trope. I endure it because I have to, and if I don't, there are people, my kin & loved ones, who will suffer because of my absence. Yes, be kind. But also recognize people are simply tired of "surviving" at maximum. It is a hard truth to digest, but sometimes where we are is where we will be for the rest of our lives. It is no fault of our own but a symptom and circumstance of a damning and oppressive ass world. I will end by saying that if no one told you today, I am glad you are here with us. It is hard to be here. And if anyone goes today, tomorrow, or anytime in the future, I am glad you have been here with us. You matter and always will. And as long as I can care for you, I will. I love you all.

How do you celebrate your people?

One thing about being in my presence is that I will always make you feel celebrated. It’s the Cancer in me!

I love making reassuring folks that their friendship/kinship is not taken for granted and I’m not quiet about it. Some ways I have celebrated friends has been by doing the following:

-Sent them flowers/edible arrangements for pivotal life changes

-Called just to have a kiki session and end the 4-hour long conversation with “well, I was just callin’ to check on ya”

-Sitting on the phone/Facetime to help friends building cooking skills to cook recipes

-Inviting them over to cook for them

-Putting into practice saying “I love you” before ending any conversation/engagement

-Making space to listen and give feedback WHEN ASKED (sometimes folks just need to be heard and then they can be given reflective thoughts later)

-I even watched my best friend’s daughter when she was a few days old so that my bff could get some rest for a few hours

So, how do you celebrate your folks???

Happy 2023 folks! I'm late af, but here nonetheless. Here's our first campaigns of the year. I'm doing two right now, since they are small asks. 

The first is a Black organizer in need of some financial help while in between jobs. Their goal is $500. Their CashApp is $lexaprotagonist and Venmo is @/s1lversurfer. 

The next person has been in a legal battle over wrongful eviction for quite some time now and is seeking funds to continue keeping them housed, fed, and safe. You can give to them via Venmo at @/NnekaAngelaO, Cash App at $NnekaAngelaO, and GoFundMe at gofund.me/1fd5e72c. 

Looking forward to a good year folks. This year I'm tracking how much I help folks raise to show folks at the end of the year how impactful and crucial this work is. So let the blessings come in, hunni!

The PHA applications are opening on Monday morning, and the folks who require it must get the help they need. This is the first time they are doing online-only applications (which is a bit confusing to me, but whatever), so there are folks who will need to be connected to resources. 

My ask from networks here is to post the names of organizations helping to get applications in for people because the website could have done a better job listing them as they said it would. If you are the loved one or close to an elder, I suggest waking them up and going over the application as early as possible. 

They project about 50,000 applications, but it will be much more. The existence of poverty is substantially understated in every sense in this city, as even the income guidelines are wild to me. 

I've made $40K before, which is not enough for one person. I've also made around $60K, and I can confirm more is needed for one person, let alone SIX people. 

Anyways, please share and help folks who need this resource where you can.

I'm starting my next crowdfunding campaign, and this one is particularly important to me as it's my sister. 

My sister has become progressively ill this past year and is finally close to getting answers, but she needs to afford the procedure to figure it out. Please visit the link in my bio and/or story to give to her if you can. 

She thanks you, and I do too. Her words are below. 
—
Hello,

My name is Aaliyah Davis and I’m from Philadelphia. I currently work with marginalized youth and with communities experiencing homelessness. It has been my passion to do this work for the last few years, but I am afraid that it all may come to a halt if I can’t overcome this obstacle:

I have an important medical procedure that will let me know if I can prevent suffering from a terrible disease. 

I am in desperate need of help. I’ve been in pain for almost a year, and now that I’m finally close to getting real answers about my health- I found out that my copay still requires me to pay $2500 out-of-pocket to get the procedure. I am in desperate need, and I hope you all can help me reach this goal by Tuesday. 

Anything can help—please help me reach my goal of doing what I need to and continue to serve my community!
With Love & Light,
Aaliyah Davis

Lesson on giving. I hear many people talk about how giving to others in their time of need feels good and that’s why they do it. If this is your specific reason for giving, you have to rethink that. Giving to others for mutual aid/support is about seeing people have what they need to live because they deserve to live. Yes, good feelings may come, but it shouldn’t be used to fill you up. 

If you do, you may be a) feeding your ego, or b) when you have nothing to give, you will beat yourself up over it.

Give because it’s crucial to love on each other. Give because you want to.

It’s late, so please forgive me, bb’s. But I have a call for support I’ve been meaning to get to for a few days.

A person reached out to me asking about being put in contact with someone who can practices consumer law for free charge. Unfortunately, I don’t know any orgs that practice consumer law for free (unless I’m reading CLS’s & Phila Legal’s sites wrong—please let me know).

But if you can, or know someone, I’d love to connect this person with someone to help!

I’m attaching their story below.
—
This person has been encountering ongoing issues with UHAUL storage, which includes the 13th street location having rats in my storage unit, then giving them grief over their service dog, lying to the AG department when they sent in a complaint, attempting to dismiss my complaint, blocking their storage unit for 5 1/2 weeks, and lying to insurance for easily provable falsities (when it rains). This person is now trying to seek restitution for the incident, and they drafted a brief with the events that happened, but they have an arbitration clause.  This person is wondering about the best way to file something.

They also just had to spend to remove all their stuff from storage which they had to throw things out because of space and rats, and they paid a mover, which was an unexpected expense.

Hey folks! Here's our new campaign. 

A Black family has been the subject of targeted harassment by their landlord and property manager. Since November 21, 2021, they have gone through a series of incidents like faux past due amounts, false accusations of being "drug dealers," utility shut-offs, claims that their disabled son damaged property, and much more. These are all forms of a self-help/informal evictions.

After exhausting their options, they are looking for financial support to find a new home. 

Their goal is $4,500. 

Their GoFundMe is: https://gofund.me/c6b46ba1 

I will also make the link available in my story and in the link in my bio. If you cannot give, share widely.

I had a long overdue Sit-A-Spell yesterday. I felt love from the minute I walked through the doors. I’m honored to have my pic on the famous porch, finally. ✨

I do not take my hat off in public spaces. It is my shield. Without it, I feel powerless. My hat helps me avoid eye contact, keeps people out of my face, and overall feels like my crown.

An hour into my visit, I took it off because I felt I could be vulnerable. TCGM had me covered, and I surrendered my defenses. She, like the Black woman who raised me, gave me solace.

My vulnerability needed to be captured here to remind me how this treasure made me feel. I hope those who visit allow it to protect and hold them, too.

Thanks for making me feel the most powerful during my powerlessness, as a colored person, who grew up a colored boy. And it doesn’t hurt that I got called pretty by a Black woman—ever!
